caption.text:
Criterion pick of the month: The Before Trilogy.

Richard Linklater works are something that you would more likely to appreciates as you get older. It's simple: Lots of his films consists mainly of dialogues, with no cool cinematography, fast-paced editing, and bombastic action set pieces, that would be wholly applauded by your younger self. 
This trilogy is no different. I watched Before Sunrise during my high school years if I'm not mistaken, and thought at that time that it was talky and unimpressive. My benchmark of a romance film at that time was probably LOVE, ACTUALLY (make no mistake, I still love that film to the bone), a hilarious, sacharine-fuelled, nudity-laden, brits import. Meanwhile this? Just two people mumbling nonsense for 1 and a half hours, come on.

But along the years, as I grew older, I would encountered this film again once in a while, and find its scripts thought-provoking, not to mention the chemistry of Julie Delpy and Ethan Hawke that is out of this world. 
The same can be said about its 2 sequel, Sunset and Midnight. BEFORE SUNSET gives you that warm feeling of a walk in a park at a Sunday afternoon, while MIDNIGHT will punch you so hard on the topic of love. #Criterion #6th #7th #8th #RichardLinklater #BeforeTrilogy

caption.text: Almost a month has passed and I still couln't get over my admiration over Denmark's public transport system, especially the train station. As well as being architecturally baroque, I were in constant wonder with the nonexistent ticket checking there. At first by the time I got my ticket, I thought that there will be some kind of machine that will scan and check the validity of my ticket. But no, you can just go through the stair and go directly to your platform and embark your train. So then I think "ah, there will be a guard onboard the train that will check the ticket". But then again, no ticket checking on the train. So it must be on the destination point, where they will absolutely ask for my ticket before I leave the station, right? No. So basically, I can just simply walk to the train, go whenever I want to be, without buying a ticket. BUT people still buy the ticket. This kind of responsibility. Even more incredible is the fact I read that Denmark has quite a great amount of atheists. So there are no "God sees our every deeds" thought. Yet, they are still buying the ticket. I am confused. #Copenhagen #Denmark #station #thirdworldthought #fujifilm_id #fujifilm #fujifilm_xseries #xt10 #AppyTraveling

caption.text:
That famous saying that life will rearrange itself to compensate for your losses? It couldn't have been truer in the case of my 1 day transit time in Copenhagen during my travel to Iceland.

The story is that, I was supposed to go to Iceland via UK. But then the UK snobbishly rejected my visa application (okay it was partly my inexperience and fault). It made me has to booked another flight to find another route. I was so close to fly via Frankfurt, since it was the cheapest option that I could find. But then on the 11th hour a friend who helped me with my travel arrangement suggest that I entered via Denmark, since I applied my Schengen through Denmark (shit, more money). And the problem didn't stop there. Of course I booked the cheapest flight from Copenhagen to Reykjavik that will leave on 2pm. But of course they had a problem on the system, so I had no other way than to book a night flight with different airlines and higher prices (more money!). But all of that leads me to this city full of amazement. Copenhagen is like a capital of culture, a capital of fantasy. You can find castle in every 500 meters that It would be impossible to not mixing up the name of  castles here (I even forgot where this photo was taken of). Sure, Iceland got everything that I expected of during the trip, but it was this city that truly caught me off-guard. So, thank you life, for rearranging yourself so that I could set foot in the kingdom of Hamlet.If I could turn back time, I wouldn't trade this experience back with a nice long day sitting at Heathrow. #Denmark #Copenhagen #castles #stattues #fujifilm #fujifilm_id #fujifilm_xseries #xt10

Menurut saya, saya termasuk 1 dari 255 juta orang yang beruntung di muka bumi ini yang mendapatkan undian untuk dilahirkan di tanah pertiwi ini.

Jujur, salah satu alasan bahwa saya tidak memiliki motivasi berlebih untuk mencari beasiswa melanjutkan kuliah di luar negeri, paling tidak untuk saat ini (disamping ya saya memang tidak pintar-pintar sekali juga orangnya) adalah ketidakyakinan saya bahwa saya bisa tidak rindu Indonesia bila meninggalkannya lebih dari 2 minggu. Dibalik kesemrawutan negara ini, saya pasti akan rindu oleh banyak hal. Kopi dan rokok yang murah. Film gratis ilegal di internet. Indomie. Cuaca tropis yang pas tidak terlalu dingin dan tidak terlalu panas. Gadis-gadis nan ayu (Saya pernah mencoba Tinder versi premium dan iseng menswipe di negara-negara yang terkenal akan kecantikannya, tapi percayalah, aktris-aktris telenovela, hollywood, maupun bollywood, mereka adalah spesies langka yang mungkin hanya mencakup 10% dari populasi negara-negara tersebut. Sedangkan disini? Naik angkot juga bisa melihat wanita cantik). Islam yang tidak terlalu mengekang namun tidak terlalu sekuler. Mudahnya akses menuju pantai maupun gunung. Dan sambal (sambal). Kombinasi hal-hal diatas saya rasa hanya ada di negara ini. Selamat ulang tahun yang ke-71 yaa Indonesia. #merahputih #merdeka #ulangtaun #tiuplilin
